      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a59b6e666c7bae51",
        "text": "Derrida's new book revolves around the literary motif of the false coin. Charles Baudelaire's short story \"La fausse monnaie,\" which is included in the volume as a bilingual fold-out, provides the perspective point: a friend of the first-person narrator gives a beggar far too much, namely a silver two-franc piece. When the narrator makes a comment about this, the friend first replies that it was a false coin, but then explains faithfully that it is a pleasure to give a person pleasure by giving him more than he expects. The narrator would still have forgiven him the false gift, also, for example, the amoral pleasure of compromising a poor person or perhaps even providing him with an interesting experience in this way, but not the self-confident stupidity of the second sentence, according to which he very economically wants to stand before himself - and Baudelaire does not forget to mention this - before God as a benefactor."
